    <text>
        <body>
            <head>81. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                    (<persName corresp="rec5nWAotd8wedNxI">Clark</persName>) to President <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d81fn1">Source: National Security
                    Council, <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security
                        Council</orgName> Institutional Files, Box SR 0106 [<gloss
                        target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss>]. Secret. Sent for action. A stamped notation at the top of the
                    memorandum reads: “Signed.”</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1983-10-04"
                        >October 4, 1983</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Decision Package on <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss> &amp; Build-down Issues for Round V of the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss> Negotiations</item>
            </list>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Issue</hi>. Does the draft NSDD (Tab A)<note n="2"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d81fn2">Printed as <ref target="#d82">Document
                    82</ref>.</note> reflect your decisions concerning <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> and the build-down initiative?</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Facts</hi>. The paper provided at Tab B<note n="3"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d81fn3">Attached but not printed is an October 3 paper,
                        “<gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss>—Preparation for Round V.”</note> reflects a position on build-down that
                was used to gain the support of both the <orgName corresp="recilTL8Sxklv18up"
                    >Scowcroft Commission</orgName> and the “group of six.”</p>
            <p>Tab C is a more detailed description<note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d81fn4">Attached
                    but not printed is an October 3 paper, “<gloss target="#t_NSC_1">
                        <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">NSC</orgName>
                    </gloss> Staff Internal Description of the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss>/Build-Down Package.”</note> of the recommended <placeName
                    corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> build-down initiative and the
                related modifications to our <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> position. It was developed by the <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">NSC</orgName>
                </gloss> staff and is not necessarily concurred in by all Departments and
                Agencies.</p>
            <p>Tab D is an <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">NSC</orgName>
                </gloss> staff analysis<note n="5" place="foot" xml:id="d81fn5">Attached but not
                    printed is an undated paper, “<gloss target="#t_NSC_1">
                        <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">NSC</orgName>
                    </gloss> Staff Analysis of the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss>/Build-down Initiative.”</note> of each of the elements of the
                recommended build-down initiative and the modifications to our <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> position. It identifies:</p>
            <quote>
                <p>—the specific elements of the build-down initiative;</p>
                <p>—the other <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss> related issues discussed at the September 29th NSPG<note n="6"
                        place="foot" xml:id="d81fn6">See <ref target="#d80fn2">footnote 2, Document
                            80</ref>.</note> and requiring decision;</p>
                <p>—the views of those who would argue against each of the elements of the
                        <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName> package recommended
                    in the draft NSDD; and,</p>
                <p>—<gloss target="#t_NSC_1">
                        <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">NSC</orgName>
                    </gloss> staff recommendations.</p>
            </quote>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">Discussion</hi>. The various issues are summarized
                best at Tab D. This summary recommends a build-down initiative along the lines of
                the guidance you previously provided and the establishment of a working group to
                discuss the initiative during Round V. It also recommends that you approve the two
                items upon which there was consensus at <pb facs="0319" n="290" xml:id="pg_290"/>
                the September 29th <orgName corresp="rec7JKzsWH5H30emC">NSPG</orgName> (further
                    <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCM</rs>
                </gloss> limits and a ban on <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                </gloss> with multiple nuclear <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga"
                    >warheads</rs>), but recommends that you defer decision on the two more
                controversial items (<gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss> limits and elimination of the 2500 <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBM</rs>
                </gloss>
                <gloss target="#t_RV_1">RV</gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sub-limit</rs>) until a later time.</p>
            <p>The draft NSDD provided at Tab A reflects the recommendations.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Recommendation</p>
            <table cols="3">
                <row>
                    <cell>
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">OK</hi>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">No</hi>
                    </cell>
                    <cell/>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>________</cell>
                    <cell>________</cell>
                    <cell>That you approve the draft NSDD provided at Tab A.<note n="7" place="foot"
                            xml:id="d81fn7">
                            <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName> initialed his
                            approval. In a statement from the Rose Garden the same day, <persName
                                corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName> declared: “When the
                                <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                                <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                            </gloss> negotiations resume tomorrow, the <placeName
                                corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United States</placeName>
                            <orgName corresp="recq1kG5wEXBQslkV">delegation</orgName> will again
                            have sustained flexibility. Within the framework of the basic principles
                            that have guided us throughout these negotiations, I am directing
                            Ambassador <persName corresp="recCAUUmNdxvAWExm">Rowny</persName> to
                            offer the following new initiatives. We’re incorporating into <gloss
                                target="#t_START_1">
                                <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                            </gloss> a series of build-down proposals. The <placeName
                                corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United States</placeName> will introduce
                            a proposal for a mutual, guaranteed build-down, designed to encourage
                            stabilizing systems. The proposal will include specific provisions for
                            building down <rs type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04"
                                >ballistic</rs>
                            <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> and,
                            concurrently, for addressing a parallel build-down on bombers.”
                            (“Remarks to Reporters Announcing New <placeName
                                corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United States</placeName> Initiatives in
                            the <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">Strategic Arms
                                Reduction Talks</rs>,” <hi rendition="simple_italic">Public Papers:
                                Reagan, 1982</hi>, vol. 2, pp. 1411–1412).</note>
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </table>
        </body>
    </text>
